TI Operationalising form postponement from a decision-making perspective
SO INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF PRODUCTION RESEARCH
LA English
DT Article
DE form postponement; delayed product differentiation; production planning
   and control; forecasting; mass customisation
ID DELAYED PRODUCT DIFFERENTIATION; MASTER PRODUCTION SCHEDULE; MULTIPLE
   FREEZE FENCES; SUPPLY CHAIN; MRP SYSTEMS; TO-ORDER; DESIGN; INVENTORY;
   STRATEGIES; FRAMEWORK
AB Form postponement means delaying the commitment of inventory to the
   final configuration of a product as long as possible. Many firms today
   are striving to redesign their products and/or their manufacturing and
   supply chain processes to implement form postponement. Opportunities
   for form postponement, however, are sometimes lost in the companies'
   production-planning processes. By focusing on the deferring of product
   mix decisions in the master production scheduling process, this paper
   shows that form postponement opportunities can be divided into two
   components: one whose pursuit necessarily requires product and/or
   transformation process redesign, the other that can be pursued by
   changing the sales forecasting and master production scheduling process
   alone. We develop an operational procedure to identify and quantify,
   for a given product family, all opportunities for form postponement and
   their two respective components. Then, we discuss and empirically
   illustrate how the proposed measurement procedure may support companies
   in changing their decision-making routines to implement form
   postponement. Finally, we set future research directions on form
   postponement suggested by our results.
